LOCATION:LILLY LIBRARY
GEO:39.167909;-86.518974
SUMMARY:The Whole World in a Book: Celebrating Madeline Kripke's Dictiona
 ry Collection
DESCRIPTION:When Kripke died in 2020\, she left behind a remarkable colle
 ction of over 20\,000 dictionaries\, as well as a rich manuscript archive
  about dictionaries\, her life\, and her collecting. In 2021\, the Lilly 
 Library acquired the collection\, keeping it intact and available for all
  to study. The spring 2026 exhibition The Whole World in a Book: Celebrat
 ing Madeline Kripke's Dictionary Collection shares some of the collection
  publicly for the first time\, curated by IU Provost Professor of English
  Michael Adams (https://english.indiana.edu/about/faculty/adams-michael.h
 tml) and Lilly Library Executive Associate Director Erika Dowell.  Madeli
 ne Kripke believed that dictionaries are an especially useful lens for ob
 serving culture. She focused on slang and other marginalized language\, a
 nd she charted the roles of dictionaries in everyday life. She collected\
 , not merely to possess\, but to share what she saw with scholars and the
  public\, and The Whole World in a Book realizes her ambition to do so.  
 This exhibition is on display until July 24\, 2026. For the Lilly Library
 's daily hours\, please visit the website (https://libraries.indiana.edu/
 lilly-library).
X-ALT-DESC;FMTTYPE=text/html:<p>  When Kripke died in 2020\, she left beh
 ind a remarkable collection of over 20\,000 dictionaries\, as well as a r
 ich manuscript archive about dictionaries\, her life\, and her collecting
 . In 2021\, the Lilly Library acquired the collection\, keeping it intact
  and available for all to study. The spring 2026 exhibition <em>The Whole
  World in a Book: Celebrating Madeline Kripke's Dictionary Collection</em
 > shares some of the collection publicly for the first time\, curated by 
 IU Provost Professor of English <a href="https://english.indiana.edu/abou
 t/faculty/adams-michael.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Michael Adam
 s</a> and Lilly Library Executive Associate Director Erika Dowell.</p><p>
   Madeline Kripke believed that dictionaries are an especially useful len
 s for observing culture. She focused on slang and other marginalized lang
 uage\, and she charted the roles of dictionaries in everyday life. She co
 llected\, not merely to possess\, but to share what she saw with scholars
  and the public\, and <em>The Whole World in a Book</em> realizes her amb
 ition to do so.</p><p>  This exhibition is on display until July 24\, 202
 6. For the Lilly Library's daily hours\, <a href="https://libraries.india
 na.edu/lilly-library" target="_blank" rel="noopener">please visit the web
 site</a>.</p><p><picture class="lw_image lw_image30107  lw_align_center l
 w_column_width_half"><source type="image/webp" srcset="https://events.iu.
